<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; padding-bottom: 5px; margin-top=
: 30px; margin-bottom: 0;">Lordstown</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Would=
n=E2=80=99t it be funny if all the electric-vehicle startups went public by=
 merging with special purpose acquisition companies, and they all marketed =
themselves to investors using ridiculously optimistic financial projections=
 predicting that they=E2=80=99d all <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/24156291.260801/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9lb=
GVjdHJpYy12ZWhpY2xlLXN0YXJ0dXBzLXByb21pc2UtcmVjb3JkLXNldHRpbmctcmV2ZW51ZS1n=
cm93dGgtMTE2MTU4MDA2MDI/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf4c5f765" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: no=
ne !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bord=
er-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">make $10 billion of revenu=
e in record time</a>, and retail investors piled in to buy their stocks, an=
d then all those projections came true and a dozen new electric-vehicle com=
panies all became world-changing giants and the people who bought their SPA=
Cs all got rich? It would be weird, right? Like right now there is a gigant=
ic successful high-profile electric-vehicle company in Tesla Inc., and ther=
e are a bunch of legacy automakers who know how to build cars and who are i=
ncreasingly focused on=C2=A0building electric cars, and then there are like=
 a dozen companies that have never built anything but have plans to build e=
lectric cars or vans or buses or trucks or whatever, and every one of them =
firmly believes that it will be somewhere between =E2=80=9Cthe next Tesla=
=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cmuch bigger than Tesla.=E2=80=9D And in 20 years I a=
ssume there will be an automotive industry, and it will be largely electric=
al, and there will be some small number of big competitors in that industry=
, and some of them will probably be currently existing legacy automakers, a=
nd one of them will probably be Tesla,[1] and maybe one or two or =E2=80=A6=
=C2=A0six? =E2=80=A6=C2=A0of them will be companies in the recent crop of S=
PAC-funded electric-vehicle startups. But will Nikola Corp. and Fisker Inc.=
 and Lordstown Motors Corp. and Canoo Inc. and Arrival Ltd. and Faraday &am=
p; Future Inc. and Lion Electric Co. and Proterra Inc. and the electric-veh=
icle companies I=E2=80=99m forgetting, not to mention the flying-electric-v=
ehicle companies,=C2=A0<em>all </em>be the next Tesla? Seems implausible. S=
ome of these things are not going to work out.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">And that=E2=80=99s fine, that=E2=80=99s life in capitalism; there is de=
mand for electric vehicles and a bunch of people start electric-vehicle com=
panies and some of them will be=C2=A0good at making electric vehicles and p=
rosper and others of them will be bad at making electric vehicles and fail.=
 And they all need lots of money to start making vehicles, so they all go t=
o investors to ask for money, and=C2=A0<em>they all say that they will be t=
he good ones</em>. Ex ante, no one goes to investors and says =E2=80=9Cther=
e are like 12 electric-vehicle companies, and maybe three of them will work=
 out, and we are not one of those, we are going to take all your money and =
noodle around for a while and then shrug and give up.=E2=80=9D They all say=
 that they will succeed! Because they all plan to succeed! They all say =E2=
=80=9Cthe total addressable market for electric vehicles is one kajillion d=
ollars and we will get 90% of it.=E2=80=9D And if you add up all of their p=
rojected market shares you get, you know, 1,000% or whatever. And somebody =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0almost everybody =E2=80=94=C2=A0is wrong.</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">And, yes, fine, some of them will be wrong about more specifi=
c, factual things. It is one thing to say =E2=80=9Cwe hope to sell a zillio=
n electric trucks in 2030=E2=80=9D; it=E2=80=99s another thing to say =E2=
=80=9Cwe already have trucks=C2=A0rolling off the assembly line=E2=80=9D wh=
en you don=E2=80=99t, as=C2=A0Nikola Corp. more or less did. That is the so=
rt of, uh, let=E2=80=99s say fraud-adjacent behavior that you sometimes get=
 with visionary startups. As I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/24156291.260801/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2=
FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMjYvc3RhcnR1cHMtc29tZXRpbWVzLXN0cmV0Y2gtdGhlLXRydXRo/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB511ed922" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;"> wrote about Nikola</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What you want, when you invest in a startup, is a foun=
der who combines (1) an insanely ambitious vision with (2) a clear-eyed pla=
n to make it come true and (3) the ability to make people believe in the vi=
sion now. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99ll tinker with hydrogen for a while and maybe=
 in a decade or so a fuel-cell-powered truck will come out of it=E2=80=9D: =
True, yes, but a bad pitch. The pitch is, like, you put your arm around the=
 shoulder of an investor, you gesture sweepingly into the distance, you clo=
se your eyes, she closes her eyes, and you say in mellifluous tones: =E2=80=
=9CCan=E2=80=99t you see the trucks rolling off the assembly line right now=
? Aren=E2=80=99t they beautiful? So clean and efficient, look at how nicely=
 they drive, look at all those components, all built in-house, aren=E2=80=
=99t they amazing? Here, hold out your hand, you can touch the truck right =
now. Let=E2=80=99s go for a drive.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or I guess Lordstown Motors Corp. was so excited about=
 making and selling electric trucks that it went around telling people it h=
ad already sold a bunch of them. But in fact it had not, <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24156291.260801/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxv=
b21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMTQvbG9yZHN0b3duLW1vdG9ycy1zYXl=
zLWNlby1jZm8tcmVzaWduLWluLWFicnVidC1kZXBhcnR1cmU/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8=
ca6ede4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #00=
0000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bo=
ttom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> =
oops</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Lordstown Motors Corp=
. shares took their biggest one-day drop ever after its two top executives =
stepped down and the electric truckmaker=E2=80=99s board found evidence of =
inaccurate statements, dimming the shine of the onetime SPAC star. =E2=80=
=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The company said in a separate statemen=
t that a board investigation concluded it had made misstatements about its =
vehicle preorders. The probe cited instances when the startup inaccurately =
claimed preorders came from commercial fleets, instead of from third-party =
management companies or =E2=80=9Cinfluencers=E2=80=9D that didn=E2=80=99t p=
lan to purchase trucks directly.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It also fo=
und that some of the preorders were placed by ostensible buyers unlikely to=
 have the resources to complete the orders or whose commitments were =E2=80=
=9Ctoo vague or infirm to be appropriately included in the total number of =
preorders disclosed.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24156291.2=
60801/aHR0cHM6Ly9pbnZlc3Rvci5sb3Jkc3Rvd25tb3RvcnMuY29tL25ld3MtcmVsZWFzZXMvb=
mV3cy1yZWxlYXNlLWRldGFpbHMvbG9yZHN0b3duLW1vdG9ycy1yZXBvcnRzLXJlc3VsdHMtc3Bl=
Y2lhbC1jb21taXR0ZWUtaW52ZXN0aWdhdGlvbg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf05d64a7" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the stateme=
nt about the board investigation</a>. The stock closed down 18.8% yesterday=
.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The story of electric-vehicle startups is=
 closely tied to the story of special purpose acquisition companies, and ev=
ery time an electric-vehicle company does something disappointing it is nat=
ural to conclude that SPACs are bad. Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/24156291.260801/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb20v=
MjAyMS8wNi8xNS9idXNpbmVzcy9kZWFsYm9vay9sb3Jkc3Rvd24tc3BhY3Mtc2VjLmh0bWw/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0bc7d4c5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">DealBook today</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">SPACs allow companies to go public earlier than traditional I.P.=
O.s, in large part because they can rely on projections to tell a story the=
y probably couldn=E2=80=99t by strictly relying on past numbers. (Such proj=
ections are not allowed in I.P.O.s.) That can be good for a biotech firm th=
at needs capital for promising research, for example. But it can be dangero=
us for investors, by allowing start-up execs to spin stories about the dema=
nd for, say, electric flying taxis, even if the chance that those vehicles =
will be widely available is remote. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">=E2=80=9CYou=E2=80=99re going to see more of this, frankly,=E2=80=9D Ton=
y Aquila, Canoo=E2=80=99s new C.E.O., told DealBook. =E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99=
s the power of the SPAC right?=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CYou can get to th=
e public markets sooner =E2=80=94 but that means you have to grow up in fro=
nt of the public.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The S.E.C. could=
 have helped with some of the issues at play here. The commission has said =
it=E2=80=99s looking at how SPACs treat their projections. If projections w=
eren=E2=80=99t allowed, or if rules forced executives to make more judiciou=
s promises, perhaps a company like Lordstown would not have made it into th=
e public market so soon via a SPAC.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">But the SPAC boom did not invent, like, the concept of visionary foun=
ders overpromising to investors. What the SPAC boom did that is interesting=
 is make it much easier for visionary founders to overpromise to <em>public=
=C2=A0</em>investors. In, like, 2017, if you had a visionary idea that wasn=
=E2=80=99t going to work out and you wanted to raise a lot of money to fund=
 it, you went to venture-capital funds or SoftBank Group Corp. and you pitc=
hed them. And they were sophisticated people who could do lots of due dilig=
ence and understand your science and engineering and blah blah blah, but le=
t=E2=80=99s not kid ourselves, they got a lot of calls wrong too. They fund=
ed a lot of visionary ideas that didn=E2=80=99t work out.</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">What they really had that was valuable was a self-consciousl=
y portfolio-based approach where they understood that they would make a lot=
 of bets on a lot of companies, and those companies would all have world-ch=
anging ideas and visionary founders and cool technology and smart engineers=
, and most of them would nonetheless fail because changing the world is har=
d, but some would succeed and return enormous amounts of money and make up =
for all the failures. And this approach worked, and works, reasonably well.=
 And a lot of people =E2=80=94=C2=A0including for instance <a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24156291.260801/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYm=
xvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTctMDctMTMvbWFpbi1zdHJlZXQtYW5kL=
XByZW1pdW0tbGlzdGluZ3M/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB952598ee" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the previous chairman of t=
he Securities and Exchange Commission</a> =E2=80=94=C2=A0noticed that the v=
enture capitalists were quite rich and ordinary investors were less rich. A=
nd they noticed that U.S. companies=C2=A0went public when they were bigger =
and older and more profitable and more stable than they did 20 years ago, a=
nd that more of the fast-growing innovative companies that contribute to ec=
onomic growth were owned by private investors. And they thought, wouldn=E2=
=80=99t it be good if public investors could have access to these sorts of =
high-tech fast-growing exciting venture-capital-ish investments?</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And there was all sorts of talk about <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24156291.260801/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
mxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMDktMjQvZWFybmluZy10aGUtcmln=
aHQtdG8tZ2V0LXN3aW5kbGVk/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc7f6d297" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: n=
one !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bor=
der-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> accredited-investor defi=
nitions</a> and encouraging initial public offerings and so forth, but also=
 independently the SPAC boom came along and now you can buy shares of=C2=A0=
like a dozen pre-revenue electric-vehicle startups. As Steven Davidoff <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24156291.260801/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb20vMjAyMS8wNi8xMi9idXNpbmVzcy9kZWFsYm9vay9TUEFDcy1kZ=
WZlbnNlLmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB04575618" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">wrote for DealBook</a> over the wee=
kend:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">SPACs are bringing riskie=
r companies to market. Stock Market 101 suggests that with more risk come m=
ore reward and more failures.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Should invest=
ors be exposed to these sorts of companies, which are inherently riskier? M=
ake your own judgment, but it wasn=E2=80=99t long ago when people were worr=
ied about start-ups staying private for too long, depriving public investor=
s of exposure to potential gains. Now that the SPAC solves this problem, re=
gulators are backpedaling.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But=
 it solves the problem not in the abstract sense of =E2=80=9Crisk=E2=80=9D =
and =E2=80=9Creward,=E2=80=9D but in the specific sense of giving public in=
vestors=C2=A0the opportunity to invest with visionary founders with world-c=
hanging ideas who might be lying to them. That's the deal that you get, as =
a venture capitalist! You fund 10 companies who say they will change the wo=
rld, and one of them will succeed and seven will fail and two are just tell=
ing you outrageous lies to get your money. And that's a good outcome for yo=
u!=C2=A0I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24156291=
.260801/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDQ=
tMjkvaWdub3JpbmctdGhlLXJ1bGVzLXNvbWV0aW1lcy13b3Jrcy1mb3ItZWxvbi1tdXNr/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cB3e08ba58" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;"> once wrote</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">For a venture capital fund, the optimal amount of securities-fraud ex=
posure is=C2=A0<em>significantly higher than zero</em>. If all the founders=
 of all the companies that you fund are telling you the complete truth, wit=
hout even a little bit of lying about how far along their technology is or =
how good their financial results are looking, then you are not funding enou=
gh aggressive and optimistic founders. For a venture capital fund, you=C2=
=A0<em>want=C2=A0</em>high-variance strategies; you want to make as many be=
ts as possible that succeed spectacularly (and give you unlimited upside) o=
r fail spectacularly (and you lose your modest investment).=C2=A0</p></bloc=
kquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a public investor in SPAC-dr=
iven electric-vehicle companies, it does seem like you can have that sort o=
f portfolio. Pretty cool, right? And yet I can see why regulators wouldn=E2=
=80=99t think so.</p><h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Ari=
al Black&quot;, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-si=
ze: 20px; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; padding-bo=
ttom: 5px; margin-top: 30px; margin-bottom: 0;">Meme zombies</h2><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">See this is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/24156291.260801/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2Fy=
dGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMTEvem9tYmllLXN0b2Nrcy1kZWZ5LWJhbmtydXB0Y3ktbG9naWMtYXM=
tbWVtZS10cmFkZXJzLWJpZC10aGVtLXVw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf0ae1f51" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> what I keep say=
ing</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s looking m=
ore and more like corporate-finance textbooks need a chapter on memes.</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Being on the brink of bankruptcy no longer seem=
s to matter much in the U.S. stock market. While that might sound like the =
beginning of a cautionary tale about the state of investing in 2021, the re=
ality is far stranger. Redditors have bid up shares of AMC Entertainment Ho=
ldings Inc. and GameStop Corp. so much that it=E2=80=99s saved them -- for =
now, at least -- from deep trouble.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">Not a chapter, even; somebody should write a whole textbook on Meme C=
orporate Finance. Maybe it will be me.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One =
aspect of=C2=A0meme-stock corporate finance=C2=A0is that bad news is good. =
A <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24156291.260801/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMDkvdGh=
lLW1lbWUtc3RvY2tzLWtlZXAtY29taW5n/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa180216f" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> standard meme-s=
tock story</a> =E2=80=94=C2=A0not the only story, certainly, but a very pro=
minent one =E2=80=94=C2=A0is that a well-known but, uh, somewhat tired comp=
any runs into business trouble,=C2=A0its stock price falls, and short selle=
rs pile in, betting on it to fail. And then people on Reddit notice this, g=
et offended by the short sellers, decide to mess with them, buy lots of sto=
ck and call options, push the stock price up to stratospheric levels, and r=
espond to any skepticism about the price by posting diamond-hand emojis and=
 buying more stock. And then the company =E2=80=94=C2=A0abortively, in the =
case of Hertz Global Holdings Inc., or grudgingly and belatedly, in the cas=
e of GameStop, or gleefully and at every opportunity, in the case of AMC=C2=
=A0=E2=80=94 sells a bunch of stock to Redditors at elevated levels to capi=
talize on the enthusiasm. And then it has lots of money to fund its project=
s.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A basic fact of ordinary, non-meme corpo=
rate finance is that bad news is bad. Like, if a company has disappointing=
=C2=A0earnings, its stock goes down. If it doesn=E2=80=99t seem to have eno=
ugh cash to pay its debt, its debt will trade at distressed levels, well be=
low par. Sometimes these things are self-reinforcing: The stock and bonds t=
rade down, nobody wants to buy more, the company has trouble funding its bu=
siness, the debt comes due and no one will refinance it, the company fails.=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">With meme stocks, those relationship=
s break down. Sometimes a company has bad news, its securities trade down, =
it can=E2=80=99t fund its activities, everything gets worse in a self-reinf=
orcing cycle and it goes out of business. Other times a company has bad new=
s, its securities trade down, a miracle occurs, its securities are short-sq=
ueezed, its stock rockets to the moon, it easily pays off its bonds at par,=
 and everything magically gets=C2=A0much better than it would have been if =
the company had had good news to begin with. It is a little hard to tell in=
 advance <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24156291.=
260801/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYt=
MTQvbW9yZ2FuLXN0YW5sZXktcy10ZWQtcGljay1tYXRjaGVkLXdpdHMtd2l0aC1nb2xkbWFuLXM=
tYmxhbmtmZWlu/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6dc53abd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> which will be which</a>.=C2=A0</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it=E2=80=99s not like it=E2=80=99s just AMC=
 and GameStop:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a broad bench=
mark of U.S. stocks known as the Russell 3000 Index, there are 726 companie=
s whose earnings don=E2=80=99t cover their interest payments, a red flag to=
 pros, according to data compiled by Bloomberg. These zombies are up an ave=
rage of 30% in 2021 -- trouncing the 13% return for the whole index -- and =
41 of them have doubled since New Year=E2=80=99s Eve.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">Even explicitly dire warnings don=E2=80=99t seem to regist=
er. A bankruptcy plan under consideration by GTT Communications Inc. would =
wipe out shareholders, which is typical in Chapter 11 cases, Bloomberg repo=
rted May 24. Nevertheless, the company=E2=80=99s stock is up about 69% sinc=
e then.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Wall Street is starting to fa=
ctor in the impact of traders drumming up enthusiasm for stocks on social m=
edia and Reddit threads. Theater operator AMC, which was on the brink of ba=
nkruptcy last year, now has a =E2=80=9Cpath to a sustainable capital struct=
ure,=E2=80=9D according to S&amp;P Global Ratings, in part because it=E2=80=
=99s been able to sell new shares amid huge demand from retail investors. V=
ideo-game retailer GameStop is now debt-free for the same reason.</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWhen looking at the debt of certain issuers=
, it=E2=80=99s becoming difficult not to take into account equity valuation=
s that may seem inflated by Reddit-driven trading, especially as companies =
such as AMC are able to monetize these valuations,=E2=80=9D said Ben Briggs=
, a credit analyst at StoneX Financial Inc. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">GTT, an internet infrastructure company, spiked to an intraday h=
igh of $4.75 on June 3 after sinking toward $1. The company caught the eye =
of Reddit traders, who pointed to its small market capitalization, high sho=
rt interest and the CEO=E2=80=99s previous business turnarounds.</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The company has repeatedly extended its forbearance a=
greement with lenders, something that=E2=80=99s been interpreted in online =
forums as a lifeline -- not a routine part of restructuring negotiations, w=
hich it is. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CA lot of retail in=
vestors are very smart,=E2=80=9D said Christian Lawrence, a strategist at R=
abobank in New York. =E2=80=9CThey aren=E2=80=99t given enough credit. But =
without a doubt many don=E2=80=99t understand the exact mechanics surroundi=
ng bankruptcy.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yeah, =
well, I said that about Hertz shareholders last year. =E2=80=9CIt is =E2=80=
=A6 possible =E2=80=A6 that many of the thousands of brand-new investors on=
 Robinhood have not carefully analyzed the capital structures to find the f=
ulcrum securities,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.=
com/click/24156291.260801/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2Fyd=
