f4b8524a319a23cBa138f7ff" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;"> I wrote</a>, snidely, as they bought up Hertz stock. <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24156291.260801/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDUtMTIvdGhlLWhlcn=
R6LWdhbWJsZXJzLXdlcmUtcmlnaHQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe1679c1e" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> They were right</=
a> and I was wrong. Maybe the bankruptcy experts and distressed-debt invest=
ors are the ones who, now, do not understand the mechanics surrounding bank=
ruptcy. Like it=E2=80=99s possible that those mechanics are =E2=80=9Cwhen y=
ou go bankrupt your stock and bonds=C2=A0trade=C2=A0up because that=E2=80=
=99s how Reddit notices you.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Everything is like this. We talked the other day about <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24156291.260801/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb=
21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMDkvdGhlLW1lbWUtc3RvY2tzLWtl=
ZXAtY29taW5n/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCa180216f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> options skew</a>. Traditionally, com=
panies are more volatile when their stock goes down than when it goes up: W=
hen your stock goes down, you are a smaller, more levered, more risky compa=
ny; when your stock goes up you are a bigger, less levered, more establishe=
d company. Meme stocks reverse that: When your stock goes up, it=E2=80=99s =
because Redditors are wildly day-trading it and it has become unmoored from=
 fundamental value; when your stock goes down, Redditors will step in to pu=
nish the shorts and prevent it from falling further. This makes option pric=
es weird, but it also upends intuitions about trading and stock prices gene=
rally. Instead of stocks falling until they hit a level of deep fundamental=
 value, or falling further and further in a doom spiral, stocks fall until =
they bounce, and then they bounce=C2=A0to the moon.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">If I write the meme-finance textbook, Part One will be title=
d like =E2=80=9CThis Is Pretty Weird Huh,=E2=80=9D and it will have chapter=
s about options skew inverting and companies emerging from bankruptcy worth=
 more than when they went in and whatever. But then Part Two will have to b=
e something like =E2=80=9CHow To Get In On It.=E2=80=9D If you are the CEO =
of a company that is considering bankruptcy, should you:</p><ol style=3D"li=
st-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Put on a suit, buckle down to sharpen your=C2=A0fi=
nancial plan, and engage in marathon meetings with creditors to try to hamm=
er out a forbearance, or</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Put on <a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24156291.260801/aHR0=
cHM6Ly93d3cucmVhZG1hcmdpbnMuY29tL3AvYXBlLWFybWllcy1hbmQtaW52ZXN0b3ItcmVsYXR=
pb25z/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB35fef8df" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;"> no pants</a> and do a bunch of Zoom inter=
views with YouTube trading influencers where you complain about short selle=
rs?</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Option 1 is the traditional answe=
r, but if Option 2 makes your stock price double and gives you enough equit=
y cushion to negotiate with your creditors from a position of strength, wha=
t are you doing with pants on? The corporate-finance opportunity set has be=
en dramatically expanded, but not in =E2=80=A6=C2=A0like =E2=80=A6=C2=A0bus=
iness-y ways? Raising a ton of money at a price unrelated to fundamental va=
lue is just a better corporate finance move than increasing your fundamenta=
l value would be. It is hard to know what to do about that. Which is why th=
ere need to be new textbooks.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or if you are=
 a hedge-fund manager, should you be buying stocks and bonds where you see =
deep fundamental value, or should you be picking stocks that might appeal t=
o Reddit and then going on Reddit yourself and pseudonymously complaining a=
bout short sellers of those stocks? =E2=80=9CThis company has no money so I=
 will bet against its bonds=E2=80=9D is not an airtight thesis these days: =
Having no money might attract short sellers, which might attract short sque=
ezes, which might make the stock shoot up, which might attract an at-the-ma=
rket equity offering, which might give the company enough money to pay off =
the bonds.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Elsewhere, here is <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24156291.260801/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvNWFjNjY3ZjQtNjNkOS00Yzc1LWJmOGItNWJkNGQ2MTA3YmMy=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfe02fd98" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;">the story of the Hertz bankruptcy auction</a>. It=
 is a high-finance story, featuring=C2=A0bankers and lawyers and hedge-fund=
 managers in conference rooms, but there=E2=80=99s also this guy:</p><block=
quote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThis was the perfect scenario, =
I just needed a couple of good bounces,=E2=80=9D says Eric Parkinson, a ret=
ail investor who likens himself to George Soros and Warren Buffett. Parkins=
on, based in Los Angeles, started speculating in Hertz shares around the ti=
me Knighthead/Certares terms were announced. =E2=80=9CI love the intersecti=
on of fear, a lazy media narrative, and where nothing makes sense,=E2=80=9D=
 he says, referring to the mainstream view that anyone buying Hertz stock w=
as a sucker.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Parkinson, like the hedge fund=
s that lawyer Andrew Glenn was pitching, noticed that Hertz bonds had jumpe=
d well over the 70 cent offer on the table. The implication was that the co=
mpany=E2=80=99s equity would soon start to be worth considerably more. Park=
inson would accumulate 67,000 shares at an average price of below $1.=C2=A0=
</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I dunno, sounds like he under=
stood bankruptcy pretty well. He made $400,000.</p>
